+{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01D8AsXJLYb5nkXdQSsEDohL","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"All 34 tests pass, build succeeds, and lint is clean. Here's a summary of the 6 bugs I fixed:\n\n### Bug 1: `src/orders/repository.ts:38` — OrderRepository.update() lost existing fields\nThe `update()` method spread only `updates` into the new object (`{ ...updates, id, updatedAt }`), discarding all existing fields. Fixed by spreading `existing` first: `{ ...existing, ...updates, id, updatedAt }`.\n\n### Bug 2: `src/billing/service.ts:25` — handleRefund not bound to `this`\nThe `handleRefund` event handler was registered without `.bind(this)`, causing `this` to be `undefined` when the handler fired via the event bus. Fixed by adding `.bind(this)`.\n\n### Bug 3: `src/inventory/service.ts:50` — Wrong guard condition in handleOrderCancelled\nThe condition `if (eventWithItems.status !== 'cancelled') return;` blocked stock release because the OrderService's cancellation event doesn't include a `status` field (so `undefined !== 'cancelled'` was always true). Removed the guard — the handler is already subscribed only to cancellation events.\n\n### Bug 4: `src/billing/calculator.ts:20-23` — Intermediate rounding caused wrong totals\nEach step (discount, afterDiscount, tax) was rounded individually before the next calculation, causing accumulated rounding errors. Fixed by computing all values without intermediate rounding and only rounding the final output values.\n\n### Bug 5: `src/orders/service.ts:99` — Off-by-one in refund window check\nThe condition `>=` rejected refunds on exactly day 30, but the business rule allows refunds through day 30. Changed to `>`.\n\n### Bug 6: `src/events/bus.ts:4` — Global handler registry leaked across tests\nThe EventBus used a module-level `globalHandlers` map shared across all instances, causing handlers to accumulate across test runs. Changed to instance-level `private handle